  "text": "The Kubernetes scheduler framework plugin extension points are defined in the staging repository at `staging/src/k8s.io/kube-scheduler/framework/interface.go`. This file contains the primary interface definitions for all scheduler plugin extension points.\n\nThe nine extension point interfaces are:\n\n1. **PreFilterPlugin** (lines 473-495): Called at the beginning of the scheduling cycle. Plugins implementing PreFilterPlugin can return a PreFilterResult to filter out nodes early in the scheduling process.\n\n2. **FilterPlugin** (lines 505-530): Called at the filter extension point to exclude nodes that cannot run a pod. This concept was previously called 'predicate' in the original scheduler.\n\n3. **PostFilterPlugin** (lines 532-554): Called after a pod cannot be scheduled. These plugins implement preemption logic or other recovery mechanisms.\n\n4. **PreScorePlugin** (lines 561-569): An informational extension point. Plugins are called with a list of nodes that passed the filtering phase.\n\n5. **ScorePlugin** (lines 582-591): Ranks nodes that passed the filtering phase. Each plugin returns a score for each node.\n\n6. **ReservePlugin** (lines 599-611): Plugins with Reserve and Unreserve methods that update plugin state when the scheduler cache is updated. Previously called 'assume' in the original scheduler.\n\n7. **PreBindPlugin** (lines 615-628): Called before a pod is bound. All prebind plugins must return success or the pod will be rejected. Includes new PreBindPreFlight method for lightweight pre-checks.\n\n8. **BindPlugin** (lines 656-665): Used to bind a pod to a node. Only one bind plugin should handle a pod; others return Skip status.\n\n9. **PostBindPlugin** (lines 632-639): Called after a pod is successfully bound to a node. These plugins are informational and typically used for cleanup.\n\n10. **PermitPlugin** (lines 641-652): Called before binding a pod. Can prevent or delay binding with timeout duration.\n\nThe framework implementation in `pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/framework.go` contains the `frameworkImpl` struct (lines 57-100) which maintains slices for each plugin type:\n- preFilterPlugins\n- filterPlugins\n- postFilterPlugins\n- preScorePlugins\n- scorePlugins\n- reservePlugins\n- preBindPlugins\n- bindPlugins\n- postBindPlugins\n- permitPlugins\n\nThe framework also defines Run* methods that execute each extension point (e.g., RunPreFilterPlugins, RunFilterPlugins, RunScorePlugins, etc.).\n\nThe plugin registry mechanism is implemented in `pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/registry.go` (lines 68-101). The Registry is a map of plugin names to PluginFactory functions. The Register method (lines 73-81) adds new plugins to the registry, and the Merge method (lines 93-101) merges multiple registries together.\n\nThe `pkg/scheduler/framework/interface.go` file provides the Framework interface definition that declares the public methods for running each extension point's plugins, while `pkg/scheduler/framework/cycle_state.go` provides the CycleState interface for managing state between plugins during a scheduling cycle.\n\nThis architecture allows the scheduler to be extensible with custom plugins that implement the specific extension point interfaces, enabling users to customize the scheduling behavior for their specific cluster requirements."
}

